of an integer, and an integer k, return the array-form of the integer num + k.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: num = [1,2,0,0], k = 34\nOutput: [1,2,3,4]\nExplanation: 1200 + 34 = 1234\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: num = [2,7,4], k = 181\nOutput: [4,5,5]\nExplanation: 274 + 181 = 455\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: num = [2,1,5], k = 806\nOutput: [1,0,2,1]\nExplanation: 215 + 806 = 1021\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= num.length <= 104\n0 <= num[i] <= 9\nnum does not contain any leading zeros except for the zero itself.\n1 <= k <= 104\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def addToArrayForm(self, num: List[int], k: int) -> List[int]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def addToArrayForm(self, num: List[int], k: int) -> List[int]:\n        ans = []\n        i = len(num) - 1\n        while i >= 0 or k:\n            k += 0 if i < 0 else num[i]\n            k, x = divmod(k, 10)\n            ans.append(x)\n            i -= 1\n        return ans[::-1]\n```\n\nThis solution iterates over the digits of the number represented by the array `num` from right to left, adding corresponding digits of `k` and handling carry-over. The result is accumulated in the list `ans`, which is then reversed to produce the final array-form of the sum.", "estimated_date": 1549756800000}